Summary:
Both fetch and axios are used to make HTTP requests in JavaScript. While fetch is native and minimal, axios comes loaded with features. But when building production-grade applications, especially SPAs or SSR frameworks like Next.js, these differences matter ‚Äî a lot.
‚úÖ Fetch
fetch('/api/data')
  .then(response => {
    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error(`HTTP error! status: ${response.status}`);
    }
    return response.json();
  })
  .then(data => console.log(data))
  .catch(error => console.error('Fetch error:', error));


Fetch does not throw on HTTP errors (like 404 or 500).
You must manually check response.ok or status codes.
